      <div class="causes">
        <div> <h3> Causes & Corrections </h3></div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> Neck strain is commonly caused by holding your head in one position for long periods of time. For most people, this usually means looking downward at a screen (aka "Tech Neck"). </p>
          <p> Due to the principle of leverage - the greater the tilt of your head, the more force it takes to hold it up against gravity. 
              So the more forward your head hangs, the more it will tilt downward as your neck compensates for the weight of your head.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="short" src="images/neck/neck-f0.jpg">
          <img class="x-long" src="images/neck/neck-strain-weight.jpg">
          <img class="short" src="images/neck/neck-f1.jpeg">
        </div>
        <div class="top-box">
          <div class="text-div">
            <p> By raising the screen to <b>eye-level</b>, the spine is able to rest in a straightened position as we sit - reducing the strain to the muscles that hold our head up. </p> 
            <p> Elevating the screen can be done with something as simple as stacked boxes/books, or with a device like a "Laptop Stand".
                These stands come in various styles, but the most important aspect to look for is a stand which eleveates the top of the screen to about <b>1-2 inches below eye-level</b>. 
                Generally, this means a stand which raises the <b>top edge of the screen</b> a minimum of <b>12 inches (30cm) above the tabletop</b>.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="image-row">
            <img class="short" src="images/neck/laptopstands-lowres-1123.jpg">
            <img class="long" src="images/neck/roost-laptop-stand-posture-image-1024x571.gif">
            <img class="short" src="images/neck/Roost-Laptop-Stand.jpg">
          </div>
          <div class="text-div">
            <p> Keep in mind though, that using a laptop stand will mean that you will also need an external keyboard and mouse - 
                otherwise you arms will be in an uncomfortable position which can put strain on your <a href="/wrists">wrists.</a> </p>
          </div>
          <br/>
        </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> Another factor may lie with the way you sleep. 
              After all, what better way to make a problem worse than to aggravate it for hours while you sleep?
              Conversely, a good sleeping position can account for hours of release. </p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="xx-long" src="images/neck/sleep-neck.png">
        </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> A healthy neck position contains a natural C-shaped curve called "lordosis". 
              But a forward neck position straightens this section of the spine - putting pressure on the spinal discs. 
              Over time, this wear and tear can lead to degenerative diseases.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="tall" src="images/neck/lordotic-natural.webp">
          <img class="short" src="images/neck/poor-posture-e1417734350694.png">
          <img class="long" src="images/neck/Different-Examples-of-Cervical-Lordosis.jpg">
        </div>
        <div class="text-div">
          <p> Although many therapies exist to treat this disorder, one of the simplest is to support this natural curve as you sleep with a "cervical pillow" (a rolled-up towel under the neck can achieve the same result).</p>
          <p> "Cervical traction" devices like a "neck hammock" are also effective corrective devices, decompressing the spinal disks and relaxing the surrounding muscles.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="image-row">
          <img class="long" src="images/neck/lordotic-neck-towel.jpg">
          <img class="long" src="images/neck/Vector_Traction.jpg">
        </div>
        <br>
