          <p class="card-title"> Chest Opening Stretch </p>
          <p class="directions"> Perform this stretch seated or standing. Interlock your fingers behind your back and look upward. Pull the shoulders back and downward. 
                                 Use a towel or partner for assistance if needed. This can also be done with arms bent and forearms parallel to the ground.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="stretch-card">
          <img src="images/neck/trapezius-side-stretch.jpg">
          <p class="card-title"> Trapezius Side Stretch </p>
          <p class="directions"> Tilt your head horizontally to the side, resting your hand on the top-side of your head. Push your head up into your hand, while using 
                                 your arm to gently resist. The opposite arm should be held behind your back.</p>
          <p class="directions"> After holding this for as long as you can, release and allow yourself to sink deeper into the stretch. Hold for a moment as you relax into the stretch.</p>
          <p class="directions"> Repeat for the other side. </p> 
        </div>
        <div class="stretch-card">
          <img src="images/neck/sternocleidomastoid-side-stretch.jpg">
          <p class="card-title"> Sternomastoid Stretch </p>
          <p class="directions"> Tilt head diagonally upward, resting your hand across your forehead. Push your head up into your hand, while using your arm to gently resist. </p>
          <p class="directions"> After holding this for as long as you can, release and allow yourself to sink deeper into the stretch. </p> 
          <p class="directions"> Repeat for the other side. If tension is more on one side, make sure to stretch the side more thoroughly. </p>  
